**Inspecting line changes**

I don't think I need to take action just yet, but I should check `git diff --numstat` to see the number of lines changed. Maybe an entire file is changing due to line endings. It's crucial to make sure that any huge end-of-line (EOL) changes are avoided, especially if it didn't show up in the search as untracked. It's always good to be cautious with these kinds of details!
**Investigating line endings**

I'm thinking about how line endings can impact file diffs in Git. If a file switches to LF (Line Feed), it might make Git show an entire file as changed when I run `git diff --numstat -- src/renderer/types.ts`. I should check the line counts to see if it’s significant. If it's too large due to end-of-line issues, I'm considering using `.gitattributes` to fix that. Maybe I'll also look into using PowerShell for preservation. Let’s check the numstat.
